question: Describe the location of the Roots in the image.
model_answer:
The image showcases "The Roots," an art installation by Washington, DC artist Christopher B. Fowler that forms part of the D.C. Public Art Collection. 
Fowler's "The Roots" is an iconic 13-foot metal tree sculpture which can be viewed on 7th Street between N and O Streets in Washington DC's Shaw/Le Droit Park neighborhood. It was installed in 2002 as part of the Chinatown Streetscape project. The Roots is a tribute to the diverse roots of the D.C. community, representing the blending of Chinese and Native American heritage in the Chinatown area. The sculpture’s leaf-like branches spell out an interwoven combination of words in Chinese and the letters that make up the title "ROOTS."
Shaw is a neighborhood in Washington, D.C., Northwest that ranks among the city's most vibrant communities. As a destination ripe for discovery — and a historic home to thriving arts communities — Shaw invites you to explore every facet of its eclectic and multicultural landscape. 

In addition to artist-run galleries featuring local, regional, and national artists in every visual discipline, Shaw also boasts the Howard Theatre, a historic music venue once nicknamed "the Apollo of U Street" that has hosted jazz greats like Duke Ellington. Discover your favorite Ethiopian restaurant along 9th Street, also known as "Little Ethiopia," and revisit African-American history at the nearby African American Civil War Museum and Memorial Freedom Foundation at the historic Grimké School building. 

Shaw's central location makes it easy to explore the rest of the city. Like Chinatown, which is set off by ornamental Chinese-style gates, and is a short walk from the X2 apartments.
